{
  "text": "configuration with one spin up electron is unaltered. The formation energy for Br is \u00c00.93 eV, a more favourable value than that for I (\u00c00.56 eV). The association energy calculated for I by Kobayashi et al. [CITATION_1] is \u00c00.10 eV (without dispersion correction). This deviates from our calculated value of \u00c00.56 eV where a dispersion correction is included. The stronger absorption of Br is due to its higher electron affinity compared to I and the shorter bond distance (C-Br v's C-I). Compared to Br and I inside C 60 , less charge is transferred. This can be due to the halide atoms inside the cage being adjacent to and thus able to gain electron density from all the C atoms of C 60 . However, inside the cage the bonding process is in opposition to Pauli repulsion; this is enough that I is more stable outside C 60 .",
